{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584723","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584723"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:55:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:55:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14789"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14789","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14789"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.39,0.11,0.33,0.06,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7480"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58631"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7480","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7480"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14789"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44033"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5084"},{"type":"tags","id":"8511"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18302"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18304"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58631","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58631"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAntihistamine medications are commonly used to treat allergic conditions. They can be classified into two main generations based on their properties.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a key difference between first and second generation antihistamines?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["First generation antihistamines readily cross the blood-brain barrier","Second generation antihistamines have greater anticholinergic effects","First generation antihistamines are more selective for H1 receptors","First generation antihistamines have less sedating effects","Second generation antihistamines have a shorter duration of action"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe key difference between first and second generation antihistamines is their ability to cross the blood-brain barrier. \u003Cstrong\u003EFirst generation antihistamines readily cross the blood-brain barrier\u003C/strong\u003E, leading to significant central nervous system effects including sedation. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESecond generation antihistamines\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Ehave\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Efewer anticholinergic side effects \u003C/strong\u003Ewhen compared to first generation antihistamines. They also have limited blood-brain barrier penetration, resulting in minimal sedation. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFirst generation antihistamines\u003C/strong\u003E are actually less selective for H1 receptors and have more anticholinergic side effects compared to second generation drugs. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe statement that \u003Cstrong\u003Efirst generation antihistamines have less sedating effects\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect, as in fact they are known for their significant sedating properties.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESecond generation antihistamines\u003C/strong\u003E typically have a longer duration of action, often allowing once-daily dosing. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["First generation antihistamines readily cross the blood-brain barrier causing sedation.","Second generation antihistamines have limited blood-brain barrier penetration, meaning they have minimal sedating effects.","Antihistamines work by competitively blocking H1 receptors."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44033"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14789"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44033","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/44033"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-02T08:46:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-02T08:47:05+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7480"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58631"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data